We’ve all seen the memes to: unplug, look UP, and remember this is a highlight reel… I’ve cut down on my time here this year because…. REAL LIFE keeps getting in the way 😂.

The addiction to likes and scrolling is REAL, and our society is failing to understand the why. With mental health issues on the same soaring trajectory as these platforms, Larissa May is here to HELP! 

A trailblazing mental health advocate, global marketing guru, and founder of #HalfTheStory , a non-profit dedicated to empowering the next generation’s relationship with social media, @halfthestory is sharing solutions; specifically to heal emotional health as it relates to the digital world this week @offthegrampodcast .

LISTEN TO THIS SHOW IF:      
- You want to learn how to avoid the negative effects of these platforms.
- You have mixed feelings about allowing your own children to be on them, and want guidance.
- You could benefit from some digital wellness best practices for yourself.

OR, if you want to tune in for some epic boss babe and change-maker energy.

I am still glowing from all of the inspiration and eye openers @livinlikelarz shared on this week’s episode.

DO NOT MISS THIS ONE!

No experience is ever wasted… as long as you learn SOMEthing.

I can remember being SO mad at myself for working so hard in school to be able to attend an Ivy League university…. To end up with a job where I got paid to NOT think (how I felt about being a screen actress).

Then, after dedicating my adolescence to vocal training, I was beyond frustrated that agents would only send me out for on-camera because 💰. After studying Shakespeare in London + putting my focus into “classical” trainings, I did NOT consider film or TV “real acting”. (I was 21… I knew very little + had big opinions 🤷🏼‍♀️.)

Finally, after years of working on TV, film, + stage, when I decided to walk away + pursue my ultimate passion -helping others heal through Yoga- I bemoaned all of the “wasted” years.

That pity party did NOT last long.
Thankfully, by then, yoga was already helping me flip my perspective 🙃.

I quickly realized that the stage training was what made me a studio-coveted yoga teacher in NYC instantly. The comfort of speaking in front of strangers is ESSENTIAL if you wish to communicate your message as a teacher or guide.

Very soon after this transition, @shape asked if I could “jot down quickly” the names + how-to instructions for each + every pose we recently shot for a fun video series (which I was comfortable doing thanks to all my years on camera). By “quickly”, she was asking me at night + needed names + how-tos for all by morning. It was the endless practice in writing at Cornell that allowed me to fulfill that request.

Of course, it was a test. I passed, and was given the opportunity to create a weekly yoga blog for #shapemagazine . That blog led to me getting hired to create Microsoft Yoga, AND the creation of @crossflow_yoga .

No experience is wasted; keep your mind open for the lessons.

Image: showing my kids @cornelluniversity proscenium stage, where I had the opportunity to perform alongside @tovahfeld + many other extraordinary talents, and learn from unparalleled directors.

Those experiences were the greatest gifts, as are all the rest. Never forget that.

Merry Christmas!! Love, Us ❤️🎄🎁🎅🏻.

First CT Christmas as a family of five. And, couldn’t be happier, or more grateful 🙏❤️🎁.

I know I’m late, but, HAPPY 2023!

Whatever holidays you celebrated / are celebrating, I hope that your winter break was peaceful and restful.

Today marks the first day in as long as I can remember that all three of my children got ON the school bus 🥳🎊 (21 pediatrician visits since school started -19 since Halloween - I just counted).

I can not WAIT to start connecting here again. I have missed you so much!

2020 and 2021 were some of the worst years of my life (by a LONG SHOT). BUT, 2022 has brought the most incredible, amazing changes to my family’s lives imaginable, and I couldn’t be more grateful for all of the strides and positive changes we made.

2022 brought me: peace of mind, grounding, a feeling of safety, happiness, joy, daily gratitude, a broader IRL community full of like minded amazing humans, and so much more.

So, while I wasn’t panting to put 2022 in my rear view mirror (other than all the germs 🦠), I am BEYOND excited for what 2023 will bring.

Every breath is a chance for a new beginning if you feel the need to reset.

So, keep your focus on everything you want in this life, remove the obstacles, and have the 2023 of your wildest dreams!

That’s my plan! What’s yours?! 👇💖

What would you do to make sure your little one could partake in all of life’s joys?  I think most parents would do anything to ensure their child has a life without limitations.  This is where we as humans start to see “problems” or “road blocks” as challenges to be overcome, rather than walls that stop us. Talk about a superpower 💥!

For me, when my youngest was finally diagnosed with hip dysplasia, I took a deep dive into research, tried everything from holistic body work to finding the best surgeon at the best children’s hospital, and have spent more hours than I will ever be able to count being a part of his healing journey.  I thank my lucky stars every day that I get to help my little angel.

My yoga teachings have always been about tapping into inner strength + resilience, but this experience added so many learnings I now share with my students.

This week @offthegrampodcast , we chat with a mother who went a different route to allow her child to partake in life - specifically - celebrations. @denisegwoodard , Founder and CEO of @PartakeFoods , sold her engagement ring& drained her bank accounts to found a company inspired by her daughter’s experience w food allergies. 

A long way from where Partake started in 2017, with self-funding & self-distribution, Partake’s first product — delicious, better for you, allergy-friendly cookies — can now be found in over 9k retailers. To date, the company has raised $19M from investors. Partake was named #45 on the Inc 5000 list in 2022. And, Denise was the first Black woman to raise more than $1 Million publicly for a CPG food startup 💥.

Denise didn’t “just” remove a limitation for her child, she is making her company, celebrations & life more inclusive for everyone.

In this episode, Denise shares how she intentionally built her company to be 90% women & 60% people of color, & shows us how any “problem” is only one company away from being solved🔥🥰.

 
🎧 Listen to this episode if: 
-You want to hear how one mama turned her child’s pain into a multi million dollar business 💥.
-You want to know how to start your own business without any investors 💪.
-You want serious inspo to break all the glass ceilings 👏!

Mommy juice 🍷, boozy brunches, mom’s night out, ladies who lunch 🥂… Our society inserts alcohol into nearly every social event - and sells it as a necessity for moms…. And then of course yells at said moms for imbibing “too much” 🤯

In honor of “Dry January” - according to our guest, a “great time to test drive sobriety”-this week @offthegrampodcast we are chatting: booze, addictions, sobriety, and everything in between, with Michelle Smith: bestselling author, keynote speaker, and the founder of Recovery is the New Black, a digital community for women living or exploring an alcohol-free life. @recoveryisthenewblack 😀🔥❤️

A mental health and addiction advocate, Michelle gives tips, and lends expertise toward normalizing sobriety in our boozy “Mommy Juice” culture. 

LISTEN TO THIS SHOW IF: 
-You or a loved one struggles with addiction or staying sober.❤️
-You can’t imagine life without your evening cocktail❤️
-You have decided that you no longer want to rely on anything external to numb the sharp edges in your life.❤️

TUNE IN!!! And let us know what YOU think 👇👇!

The first workshop I taught teaching others to do the same, was the moment I knew I needed to devote my life to sharing that strength/ feeling/ knowledge with others.

There is nothing more powerful than the knowledge that you can literally hold yourself up with your own two hands. But… how to earn a living sharing that? That was / IS an entirely different story.

Do you ever look at an entrepreneur who’s been continuously successful for decades and think: “how the hell do they sustain that?” Add motherhood to the mix, and it becomes even more mind bending 🤯😍.

@stacyigel shares everything from: the importance of authenticity (which I can SO relate to), to her path to kicking ass in a male-dominated world, to wisdom on how to turn chaos into success and achieve your goals on your own terms. Want more? Keep your eyes peeled for Stacy’s new book, "Embracing the Calm in the Chaos: How to Find Success in Business and Life Through Perseverance, Connection, and Collaboration."

LISTEN TO THIS SHOW IF: 
-you want to learn the art of turning chaos into opportunity
-you're interested in achieving success on your own terms 
-you're eager to discover the secret sauce for building a purpose-driven brand

After the explosive episode (and no, I’ll never tell which one, but you are more than welcome to guess 😘😘), @nycfitfam @meaghanbmurphy and I took the time to do some soul searching, and realized some hard truths about ourselves, the show, and YOU.

Does yoga at work look like this for you? 🙃

I kid, I kid. But, I’m all seriousness, does any of the following sound familiar? Zero boundaries. Overwhelm. More work, without more compensation. Split focus. Mega multi-tasking. Less and less budget... Just a few changes that seem to prevalent in this new work-from-home reality….

It can feel like being happy (or even simply believing that you have things under a modicum of control) at work - whether you’re an employee or the one in charge - feels nearly (if not completely) impossible these days. With all the uncertainty, how can we move towards a better, more aligned, HAPPIER professional environment? What can an employee do to ensure job security while still protecting their peace? What can employers do to boost morale and help their teams thrive?

Pre-pandemic, I was going into corporations every week and teaching mini yoga/ meditation/breath work classes. It did not escape my notice that it was stressful for the employees to have to stop their workday to do this. It felt like they were just going to have to stay that much later that night to finish their work 🫣.

This week @offthegrampodcast , we interviewed Laura Putnam, speaker, author, and CEO of Motion Infusion, specializing in workplace wellness.

@lauraputnamauthor shares her insights on the latest  workplace trends.  Want to know if the hybrid work model is here to stay? Wondering how employee activism will affect the workplace? It’s hard to put in words what @crystaltheatre_ct means to me. My journey began when I signed up for some art classes at a camp called Creative Summer in Greenwich as a child. There was a mixup + the 1st morning had me slated for theatre + singing 😱. Cheryl Kemeny, founder of Crystal Theatre, was leading these classes, and had every camper do a singing audition that day… solo 😱. I didn’t know how to sing that day, but I was an eager student.

I never switched back to my intended schedule. Through Cheryl, I fell in love with singing + when the summer was over, I followed her to Crystal Theatre in Norwalk. The 1st show I did there was the world premiere of Cheryl’s original musical, “The Snow Queen”. She entrusted me to be her leading lady, and for the first time in my life, I felt what it was to be believed in.

The path Cheryl set me on - a path that allowed me to understand that I was a capable human, believe in myself, and feel comfortable commanding the attention of a room - was necessary to become the person, yoga teacher, and mother I am today.

I can’t imagine who or where I would be without Cheryl, or the community she and the other founders created with Crystal Theatre.

So, when I got the invitation to be a part of the 35th anniversary benefit show, I couldn’t fathom not jumping at the opportunity.

And, what a jump that was. The magic of Crystal Theatre was brought back to me in full force, re-living:  how Cheryl, Char (founder of @dancedimensionsnorwalk ) + Alex bring out the best in everyone, the amazing bonds one can form with cast mates + directors alike, what true support looks + feels like, the power of watching others grow into + thrive in their roles, seeing the miracle of everything coming together at the last moment for one spectacular performance… it all feels too good to be true.

Endlessly grateful to Cheryl, Char, Alex + @laszlosbalazs for making “A Spinning Tale” magic. And, of course, the endlessly talented (+ hilarious) cast. What a trip! Can’t wait for the next.

If you are in Fairfield county, get your kids into Crystal! If not, come catch a show!

A year ago, I couldn’t do this 👆. And, in my darkest moments, I wondered if I would ever feel whole again.

A healing journey is NOT for the faint of heart. If you are lucky enough never face this particular demon, I am SO happy for you. If you’ve been here over the past 18 months, you’ve seen first hand a slice of the grueling work I have done to heal.

Between surgery, painfully slow moving OT, daily physical, acupuncture, cleanest diet imaginable, infrared sauna, PEMF therapy, Chinese herbs, multiple trauma therapists + a whole slew of other treatments that were incredibly challenging both mentally + physically... 

One of the only things I didn’t try (bc my attackers smashed my right wrist to smithereens) was journaling… That’s the path to healing that this week’s @offthegrampodcast guest advocates  for.

In one of my favorite episodes to date, we are speaking with @drgabbypelicci , who specializes in creating wellbeing at the intersection of Integrative Health, Spirituality + Storytelling.

And, for the first time in my life, when I opened up her new book, “All This Healing Is Killing Me” a memoir, I could NOT put it down until I had read it cover to cover - it is TRANSFORMATIONAL.

A PH.D., University Professor of Integrative and Holistic Medicine, and coach, Dr. Gabby spent decades experiencing + learning different healing modalities. She completed her doctoral work with a dissertation on women healers, and studied plant medicine with indigenous healers in New Mexico + Guatemala. She also gives us the 411 on her latest - psychedelics! Dr. Gabby’s first book, “All This Healing Is Killing Me”, a memoir, speaks to mental illness, loss + grief, complex PTSD & the long journey to healing + trauma recovery. Buckle up, because we get into it ALL ❤️‍🩹.

🎧LISTEN TO THIS SHOW IF:
💥You want to learn why we are only as sick as our secrets 🤫.
🫣 You’re interested in how childhood trauma impacts our physical and mental health — as well as our adult relationships 🤝.
💪 You want to learn how to take control of your own narrative, and write yourself a happy ending write ✍️👏.

DO NOT MISS THIS EPISODE!

The mind is our most powerful tool. Are you using it to your benefit?

Believe you can, and you will 💖.

Every new beginning comes from some other beginning’s end 🎶, and it’s time for a new beginning 💖.

It has been such an honor and privilege to spend the last four years interviewing some of the most incredible, wise, wonderful, and interesting humans imaginable, and then sharing them with all of you 🙏.

Thank you. From the bottom of my heart: thank you for tuning in, and being a part of our Off The Gram community 💗.

Of course, thank you to all of our incredible guests for sharing your knowledge and time with us and our @offthegrampodcast listeners.

We started #offthegrampodcast because there was so much misinformation here on the gram, and we wanted to give a literal microphone (off the gram and on) to those who were qualified to help, and those who had actual wisdom to share. Often times, the actual experts aren’t the ones with a platform. Because, they focus most of their time and attention honing their craft, doing more research, helping people IRL, and so much more. 

2019 was a time when there seemed to be endless “expert self-marketers” who had no business (education, experience, or any sort of credentials) dispensing advice here. And, the only expertise they truly had was in marketing themselves as something or someone they were not. Those people hurt people. Many, many people got hurt. 

Our mission at Off The Gram, from well before we started shooting or airing episodes, was to cut through the confusion created by the flashy / clickbait dangerous self-proclaimed “experts”, and amplify the voices of actual experts. TO HELP.

We pivoted many times in response to what we felt best served our community, and, I am beyond proud of what we accomplished, the stories we shared, the help we offered, and the work we did @gothamproductionstudios .

After more than four years from brainstorming up Off The Gram, we feel like we accomplished what we set out to do. And today, we air our 186th and last episode. Everything you could want to know is in it - all the whys, hows, and more. Tune in one last time, and THANK YOU 🙏💘.

The past 4 years have been so chaotic for me, that I feel like I haven’t been anywhere close to as intentional as I would have liked. I  have felt very reactive, rather than proactive, which is never my preferred state. 

So, this year, I decided that words would be a nice reminder / intention. The ones that keep coming up for me are:

1. Peace 🕊️
2. Santosha (Sanskrit for contentment) 😌
3. Create 💪

Yoga is a PRACTICE. We practice again and again and again. You never get “there” (wherever “there” is). You roll out your mat, and continually practice how you want to FEEL.

I love challenging poses because life is full of challenges. And, the more I practice how I want to FEEL amidst a challenge on the mat, the better I get at feeling that way when they arise off the mat (like this morning, when I woke to our newly finished basement flooding AGAIN, with my husband away AGAIN 🤪).

I love heart openers because they remind me to open my heart again and again and again with grace and ease, regardless of how it may have been hurt. 

What is your favorite application of yoga off your mat? I’d love to know 👇💕🙏.
